
Introduction to Recursion
What is Recursion?

Recursion is a programming technique where a function calls itself to solve a problem. Instead of solving the whole problem at once, recursion breaks it into smaller and similar subproblems until it reaches a stopping condition.

Simple Definition:

Recursion is a process in which a function calls itself until a base case is reached.

How Recursion Works

Every recursive function has two important parts:

1. Base Case

The base case is the stopping condition. It prevents the function from calling itself forever.

if n == 0:
    return

Without a base case, the program will run into infinite recursion and eventually cause a Stack Overflow error.

2. Recursive Case

The recursive case is where the function calls itself with a smaller or simpler input.

function(n - 1)

Each recursive call brings the function one step closer to the base case.

Recursion Flow
Function Call
      │
      ▼
Check Base Case
      │
 ┌────┴────┐
 │         │
Yes        No
 │         │
Stop    Do Some Work
           │
           ▼
    Call Function Again
           │
           ▼
       Repeat
Example
def print_numbers(n):
    if n == 0:
        return

    print(n)
    print_numbers(n - 1)

print_numbers(5)
