Why Use Recursion?

Recursion is useful when a problem can be divided into smaller versions of the same problem. It makes code cleaner and easier to understand for many complex problems.

Common applications include:

Factorial
Fibonacci Series
Binary Search
Tree Traversal
Graph Traversal (DFS)
Merge Sort
Quick Sort
Tower of Hanoi
Backtracking Problems
Advantages
Makes code shorter and easier to read.
Helps solve complex problems with simple logic.
Best suited for tree and graph algorithms.
Commonly used in divide-and-conquer algorithms.
Disadvantages
Uses extra memory because each function call is stored in the call stack.
Can be slower than loops.
Too many recursive calls may cause a Stack Overflow.
Debugging recursive functions can be difficult for beginners.
Recursion vs Iteration
Recursion	Iteration
Function calls itself	Uses loops (for or while)
Requires a base case	Requires a loop condition
Uses call stack memory	Uses less memory
Better for recursive problems like trees	Better for simple repetitive tasks
Time Complexity

The time complexity depends on the problem.

Problem	Time Complexity
Print Numbers	O(n)
Factorial	O(n)
Fibonacci (Simple Recursion)	O(2ⁿ)
Space Complexity

Recursion uses the call stack to store function calls.

If there are n recursive calls, then:

Space Complexity = O(n)
Key Points to Remember
A recursive function calls itself.
Every recursive function must have a base case.
The recursive call should always move toward the base case.
Missing the base case leads to infinite recursion and Stack Overflow.
Recursion is widely used in trees, graphs, divide-and-conquer, and backtracking algorithms.
Summary
Recursion is a technique where a function calls itself.
It solves large problems by breaking them into smaller subproblems.
Every recursive function contains a base case and a recursive case.
It is a powerful technique used in many algorithms and data structures, especially where problems have a recursive nature.
